node.text: Last nights blue moon! Fun fact the term ‘blue moon’ has nothing to do with the color of the moon. This is a seasonal blue moon, which means it’s the third of four full moons in a season. My shot coincidentally is blue because of the presence of iridescent clouds, making the moon seem actually blue! I’m going to be sending the full res file of one of these images to my mailing list subscribers in 24hrs, so comment which one you want and subscribe in the link in my bio!

node.text: Jupiter at opposition with two of its moons, Io and Europa. I’m a couple days late but opposition occurs when the earth sits directly between the sun and another planet, in this case Jupiter. This means it will appear it’s brightest in the night sky. If you see a bright star in the East a bit after sunset, it’s Jupiter! This is how the planet appears through my telescope on a rare night of pretty good seeing. And fun fact that closer dot is a moon that has oceans under its icy surface that may contain life! Hope y’all enjoy!

node.text: An extremely high res up close view of the western veil nebula. This is a portion of an exploded star that died some 15,000 years ago. The intense radiation from the supernova of the star caused these intense and intricate shockwaves of ionized gas to expand through space. This is a bicolor narrowband image captured from Sierra remote observatory. If you want to edit this data for yourself, check the link in my stories. If you want to sign up for the data service from this telescope as well, you can find more info through that link. Hope you all enjoy!

node.text: First light from my new backyard! This is the elephant trunk nebula in Cepheus, one of my favorite nebulas in the sky. It is a star forming region 2400 light years away, and it’s named after the big spire at the bottom. This is a narrowband image, meaning the colors in the image are false. Such an image would not be possible from light pollution without the use of these filters. I shot this with 25hrs of data taken with the QHY600 and radian raptor. Hope you all enjoy this image!

node.text: Today’s sun through some very thick wildfire smoke! If you want a the full res file of this image, subscribe to my mailing list, I will be sending this image out to subscribers in 24hrs. Link in my bio. The sun’s surface is still relatively calm. The activity on the sun follows an 11 year cycle, which we are on the way out of the bottom of right now. Over the next couple years the activity on the sun is going to continue to ramp up, but for now it is calm. Interestingly, the shape of the corona is affected by this behavior as well. I hope to show you guys some images of this phenomena soon, I’m learning to process coronagraph data from the SOHO mission. Hope you enjoy the image!

node.text: The infamous pillars of creation, 7,000 light years away from earth in the constellation Serpens, in the heart of the eagle nebula. They are towers of gas and dust which contain many forming stars, which will one day blow the pillars away with their radiation. In fact the pillars are likely already gone, but the light won’t reach us for another 7,000 years. This is probably one of the highest resolution amateur images captured of the region at around 0.2 arc seconds per pixel. No noise reduction or AI sharpening was used to produce this image, just good data! I’ve attached the Hubble image of this region for reference, you will all probably recognize it. Hope you all enjoy the image!

node.text: One year anniversary of the great comet neowise! Probably the most photographed comet in history. Comets are a great reminder that things in the sky are constantly changing, sometimes slowly but also sometimes quickly. Over the course of a month this comet went from being a small dot visible before sunrise, to a massive bright comet. Here is an image I captured of the comet above Seattle from bellevue. The scale of this image is completely true to real life, the comet when properly processed DOES appear this large in the sky. I can’t wait for the next one to come, some of the best times I’ve ever had were spent chasing this comet! Hope you all enjoy.

node.text: 10,000 years ago this used to be a star! However it burned up all its fuel, and shedded its outer layers into deep space, leaving behind a white dwarf star and one of the best planetary nebula in the sky. This is m27 the dumbbell nebula, a planetary nebula 1300 light years away in the constellation Vulpecula. This one can easily be seen with a pair of binoculars. This image was made from 22hrs of data captured with the 16” RCOS at Sierra remote. Hope y’all enjoy!

node.text: This image of the sun took 60 gigabytes of image to create. I captured this image earlier today under mediocre seeing conditions, but there is still plenty detail to look at. There’s some sunspot activity and a nice prominence. This was shot using the daystar quark from @optcorp, along with an ASI183mm. Hope you guys enjoy the image, and have a great 4th of July! Don’t start any fires as big as this one.
